The Minister of Science  and Technology, Ogbonnaya Onu, yesterday described the recent incidents of earth tremor in some parts of the country as a wake-up call for stakeholders in the field of forecasting, detection and efficient management of all known natural disasters. Commissioning some projects in  Plateau State and Bauchi State, he said the recent earth tremor in Abuja and other parts of Nigeria was terrible and would be tackled squarely. “I see the commissioning of the projects that were funded by the President Muhammadu Buhari led government as sacrosanct to the realization of our collective resolve to continue to monitor those activities that may give rise to earthquakes in future, as well as mitigating their impacts when they occur since nobody can stop their occurrence every 17 agencies under his ministry federal government. “Following the recent incidences of the earth tremors and building collapses in parts of the country, the federal government is poised at adopting the necessary measures to ensure the establishment of seismic building codes and enforcement of same in Nigeria after the necessary legislation to guide against the unwholesome practice of quackery in the construction and building industry,” he said. According to the minister, the recent deaths resulting from such manmade disasters like building collapse are regrettable and this calls for total overhaul of the building industry in Nigeria. “It has become imperative for the ministry to intensify research and innovation as well as increase the awareness among the people in the country of the importance of science and technology to their daily needs and effective coordination of the nation’s tertiary and research institutes that can translate into products and services,” he said. A wake-up call on Abuja earth tremors Earth tremor: Scientists warn Nigerians against indiscriminate blasting of rocks Abuja tremor: Experts rule out earthquake possibility Dear Esteemed reader, As part of our drive t